-- Money Managers Boost Bullish Bets in London Cocoa a 2nd Week
-- B y   I s i s   A l m e i d a
-- 2013-03-11T13:35:13Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-03-11/money-managers-boost-bullish-bets-in-london-cocoa-a-2nd-week-1-.html
Money managers  boosted bets  on
rising prices for cocoa traded in  London  for a second
consecutive week, according to NYSE Liffe, the derivatives arm
of NYSE Euronext.  Net-long positions, or bets on higher prices, rose to
11,406 futures and options in the week ended March 5, the
commitments of traders report published today on the exchange’s
 website  showed. That’s up from 10,780 contracts a week earlier.
Bets on rising prices climbed for a second week after reaching
an 11-month low in the week ended Feb. 19. The beans used to
make chocolate fell 1.8 percent in the period.  In robusta coffee, money managers  reduced their net-long 
position to 25,941 futures and options, the data showed. That
compares with 26,829 contracts a week earlier. Robusta coffee,
used to make instant drinks, rose 0.2 percent in the period.  Money managers’  net-short positions , or bets on lower
prices, in white, or refined, sugar climbed to 11,329 contracts
from 10,837 futures and options a week earlier. The sweetener
gained 1.6 percent in the period.  In feed wheat, money managers increased their net-short
position to 367 futures and options from 366 contracts a week
earlier. The grain rose 0.1 percent in the period.  To contact the reporter on this story:
